<div class="news-item">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0">History &amp; Background</h3>
    <p>
        The HP Prime is highly unusual for an HP calculator. The RPN is
        lacklustre, the LCD is a touchscreen, and there's no RPL?
    </p>
    <p>
        You know what they say. If it doesn't look like a duck (It kind of
        does, but that's beside the point), doesn't swim like a duck, and
        doesn't quack like a duck, then it's probably not a duck. It's not
        an HP calculator.
    </p>
    <p>
        Indeed, the Prime is made by contract for HP by a Czech company
        called Moravia Consulting, who also does contracts for Sharp and
        Rebell.
    </p>
    <p>
        The differences between the Prime and home-grown HP calcs show
        here.
    </p>
</div>

